Think of the prototype chain as JavaScript's way of saying:

> "If an object doesn't have a property, ask its parent object."



Example

const animal = {
  eats: true
};

const dog = {
  barks: true
};

Object.setPrototypeOf(dog, animal);

console.log(dog.barks); // true
console.log(dog.eats);  // true

How dog.eats works

1. JavaScript looks for eats inside dog.

{ barks: true }

Not found ❌


2. It follows the prototype link to animal.

{ eats: true }

Found ✅


3. Returns true.



Visual

dog
 ↓
animal
 ↓
Object.prototype
 ↓
null

Real-world analogy

Imagine you ask your younger brother (dog) for a book.

If he has it → he gives it.

If not → he asks your father (animal).

If father has it → you get it.

Otherwise → "not found".


That's exactly how the prototype chain works in JavaScript.

One-line definition

Prototype chain = the sequence of objects JavaScript searches through when a property or method is not found on the current object.
